{{Distinguish|Vincible ignorance|Invincible ignorance fallacy}}
The term "invincible ignorance" has its roots in [[Catholic theology]], where — as the opposite of the term [[vincible ignorance]] — it is used to refer to the state of persons (such as pagans and infants) who are ignorant of the [[Christianity|Christian]] message because they have not yet had an opportunity to hear it. The first Pope to use the term officially seems to have been [[Pope Pius IX]] in the [[allocution]] ''Singulari Quadam'' (9 December 1854) and the [[encyclical]]s ''Singulari Quidem'' (17 March 1856) and ''Quanto Conficiamur Moerore'' (10 August 1863). The term, however, is far older than that. [[Aquinas]], for instance, uses it in his ''[[Summa Theologica]]'' (written 1265–1274),<ref>Aquinas, [http://www.newadvent.org/summa/2076.htm#article2 ''Summa Theologica'' Ia IIae q.76 a.2]</ref> and discussion of the concept can be found as far back as [[Origen]] (3rd century). {{Citation needed|reason=Where did Origen say this?|date=August 2018}}
When and how the term was taken by logicians to refer to the very different state of persons who pigheadedly refuse to attend to evidence (see [[Invincible ignorance fallacy]]) remains unclear, but one of its first uses was in the 1959 book ''Fallacy: The Counterfeit of Argument '' by W. Ward Fearnside and William B. Holther.<ref>Fearnside, W. Ward and William B. Holther, ''Fallacy: The Counterfeit of Argument'', 1959. {{ISBN|9780133017700}}.</ref>
==See also== *[[Vincible ignorance]] *[[Fate of the unlearned|Destiny of the unevangelized]] *[[Future probation]] *[[Invincible error]] *[[Willful blindness]] *[[Invincible ignorance fallacy]]
