{{Jainism}}

The history of '''Jainism in Africa''' is relatively short when compared with the histories of [[Jews and Judaism in Africa|Judaism]], [[Christianity in Africa|Christianity]] and [[Islam in Africa|Islam]] on the same continent. There are about 20,000 Jains and around 10 Jain organizations in Africa.{{Sfn|Dundas|2002|p=271}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=3s1vxWrqohMC&pg=PR10|edition=2 |title=Jainism: The World of Conquerors|first=Natubhai|last=Shah|publisher=Sussex Academic Press|date=1998 |isbn=9781898723974 }}</ref>

==History==
Jainism entered Africa during the late 19th century, when Jains first emigrated from India to Kenya, and then to Uganda, Sudan and Tanzania.<ref name="google1">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=loQkEIf8z5wC|p=263 |title=Jainism: A Pictorial Guide to the Religion of Non-Violence|first1=Kurt |last1=Titze|first2=Klaus |last2=Bruhn|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass Publication |isbn=9788120815346 |year=1998 }}</ref>

An exodus of Asians from Uganda in 1972 due to [[Idi Amin]]'s policies forced some Jains to migrate elsewhere, like Australia,<ref name="google1"/> North America and Europe.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=5_EdL2FtIqQC|p=88 |title=Jainism and Early Buddhism: Essays in Honor of Padmanabh S. Jaini|publisher=Jain Publishing Company| first=Olle|last= Qvarnström |isbn=9780895819567 |year=2003 }}</ref>

==Jainism in Kenya==
Jainism in Kenya has been present for about 100 years.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=jAcXAAAAIAAJ |title=Kenya churches handbook: the development of Kenyan Christianity, 1498-1973|first=David B.|last=Barrett|publisher=Evangel Publication House |year=1973 }}</ref> It is practiced by a small community that actively organizes Jain conventions,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-star.co.ke/news/article-72919/jain-convention-takes-places-nairobi |title=Jain Convention Takes Places In Nairobi |publisher=The Star |date=2011-01-18 }}</ref> film festivals<ref>{{cite web|last=Jabbal |first=Harleen |url=http://allafrica.com/stories/201212120701.html |title=Kenya: Young Jains of Nairobi's Film Show |publisher=allAfrica.com |date=2012-01-02 }}</ref> and other community programs.

There are Jain temples in [[Nairobi]] and [[Mombasa]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=epbpZJoiEAUC|title=DK Eyewitness Travel Guide: Kenya: Kenya|first=Philip |last=Briggs|publisher=DK Publishing |date= 2011-09-01 |isbn=9780756684457|p=31 }}</ref> Jains are among the most successful and prosperous businessmen in Nairobi and other bigger towns.{{sfn|J.N.K. Mugambi|2010|p=108}}

==Jainism in South Africa==
Jains emigrated to South Africa under British colonial rule in India and South Africa, and exceeded in trade and business.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=VwsbJgJX84cC|p=117 |title=Cultural and Religious Heritage of India: Jainism|first1=Suresh K.|last1=Sharma|first2=Usha|last2=Sharma |publisher=Mittal Publications |isbn=9788170999577 |year=2004 }}</ref> Due to the high number of Jain tourists, in addition to the resident Jain community, many South African restaurants offer [[Jain food]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/interview_many-sa-hotels-offer-jain-veg-cuisine_1227869 |title=Many SA hotels offer Jain, veg cuisine - India - DNA |publisher=DNA India |date=2009-02-05 }}</ref>

